 British, French, German, Italian and American. Various colonial spaces are considered, from the Mediterranean, Middle East, Africa, Australia, Asia and the Americas, and in doing so, the contributors offer new insights into the nature of imperialism and colonial settlement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aColoniesxEconomic conditions. 0aColoniesxSocial conditions. 0aDystopiasxHistory. 0aDystopias. 0aImperialismxEconomic aspects. 0aImperialismxHistory. 0aImperialismxSocial aspects. 0aUtopias. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBambuk gold.  aBritish Mesopotamian El Dorado.  aDarien project.  aEl Dorados.  aFrench Indochina.  aGerman Templer colonies.  aGreek expectations.  aPalestine.  aPatagonia.  aScottish adventurism.  aSwan River Colony.  acolonial settlement.  adystopias.  aimperial causality.  aimperialism.  autopias.1 aBaratieri, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrows, Leland Conley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDroessler, Holger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinaldi, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, Matthew P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHennessey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensz, Felicity, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKenzie, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatters, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Ruth A., econtributor.